//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: has no order
//
// Ordering is total *within* a type, not across types. A union has more than one
// shape, so `<` on it would need an invented rank between the arms — the
// cross-type order that Erlang and Elixir define and this language declines,
// because it turns a comparison mistake into a silent answer.
//
// This typechecks under the overlap rule — it is the same type on both sides —
// so it takes its own check. `==` on the same value is fine and stays total.

use std::io;

fn worse(v: i64 | :none) -> bool {
    v < v
}

fn main() {
    io::println("#{worse(1)}");
}
